[src:openconfig/grpc] gRPC uses HTTP/2 for transport, Protocol Buffers as the interface description language, and provides features such as authentication, bidirectional streaming and flow control, blocking or nonblocking bindings, and cancellation and timeouts.
[src:openconfig/grpc] It generates cross-platform client and server bindings for many languages.
[src:openconfig/grpc] The most common usage scenarios include connecting services in a microservices style architecture, or connecting mobile device clients to backend services.
[src:openconfig/grpc] gRPC's use of HTTP trailers makes it impossible to implement a gRPC client in a browser, instead requiring a proxy.
[src:openconfig/grpc] From about 2001, Google created a general-purpose RPC infrastructure called Stubby to connect the large number of microservices running within and across its data centers.
[src:openconfig/grpc] In March 2015, Google decided to build the next version of Stubby and make it open source.
[src:openconfig/grpc] gRPC supports the usage of Transport Layer Security (TLS) and token-based authentication.
[src:openconfig/grpc] Connection to Google services must use TLS.
[src:openconfig/grpc] There are two types of credentials: channel credentials and call credentials.
[src:openconfig/grpc] For token-based authorization, gRPC provides Server Interceptor and a Client Interceptor.
[src:openconfig/grpc] gRPC uses Protocol Buffers to encode data.
[src:openconfig/grpc] Protocol buffers provide a serialization format and an interface definition language.
[src:openconfig/grpc] Some of the software tools used for testing gRPC implementations include Postman, ezy, Insomnia, and Step CI.
[src:openconfig/grpc] Many organizations use gRPC, including Uber, Square, Netflix, IBM, CoreOS, Docker, CockroachDB, Arista Networks, Cisco, Juniper Networks, Spotify, Zalando, Dropbox, and Google as the original developer.
[src:openconfig/grpc] The open source project u-bmc uses gRPC to replace Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).
[src:openconfig/grpc] On 8 January 2019, Dropbox announced that the next version of "Courier", their RPC framework at the core of their service-oriented architecture (SOA), would be migrated to be based on gRPC, primarily because it aligned well with their existing custom RPC frameworks.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] In computer science, **model checking** or **property checking** is a method for checking whether a finite-state model of a system meets a given specification (also known as correctness).
[src:openconfig/model-checking] This is typically associated with hardware or software systems, where the specification contains liveness requirements (such as avoidance of livelock) as well as safety requirements (such as avoidance of states representing a system crash).
[src:openconfig/model-checking] In order to solve such a problem algorithmically, both the model of the system and its specification are formulated in some precise mathematical language.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] To this end, the problem is formulated as a task in logic, namely to check whether a structure satisfies a given logical formula.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] This general concept applies to many kinds of logic and many kinds of structures.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] A simple model-checking problem consists of verifying whether a formula in the propositional logic is satisfied by a given structure.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Property checking is used for verification when two descriptions are not equivalent.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] During refinement, the specification is complemented with details that are unnecessary in the higher-level specification.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] There is no need to verify the newly introduced properties against the original specification since this is not possible.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Therefore, the strict bi-directional equivalence check is relaxed to a one-way property check.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] The implementation or design is regarded as a model of the system, whereas the specifications are properties that the model must satisfy.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] An important class of model-checking methods has been developed for checking models of hardware and software designs where the specification is given by a temporal logic formula.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Pioneering work in temporal logic specification was done by Amir Pnueli, who received the 1996 Turing award for "seminal work introducing temporal logic into computing science".
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Model checking began with the pioneering work of E.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Clarke, Emerson, and Sifakis shared the 2007 Turing Award for their seminal work founding and developing the field of model checking.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Model checking is most often applied to hardware designs.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] For software, because of undecidability (see computability theory) the approach cannot be fully algorithmic, apply to all systems, and always give an answer; in the general case, it may fail to prove or disprove a given property.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] In embedded-systems hardware, it is possible to validate a specification delivered, e.g., by means of UML activity diagrams or control-interpreted Petri nets.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] The structure is usually given as a source code description in an industrial hardware description language or a special-purpose language.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Such a program corresponds to a finite-state machine (FSM), i.e., a directed graph consisting of nodes (or vertices) and edges.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] A set of atomic propositions is associated with each node, typically stating which memory elements are one.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] The nodes represent states of a system, the edges represent possible transitions that may alter the state, while the atomic propositions represent the basic properties that hold at a point of execution.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Formally, the problem can be stated as follows: given a desired property, expressed as a temporal logic formula p , and a structure M with initial state s , decide if $M,s\models p$ .
[src:openconfig/model-checking] If M is finite, as it is in hardware, model checking reduces to a graph search.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Instead of enumerating reachable states one at a time, the state space can sometimes be traversed more efficiently by considering large numbers of states at a single step.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] When such state-space traversal is based on representations of a set of states and transition relations as logical formulas, binary decision diagrams (BDD) or other related data structures, the model-checking method is *symbolic*.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Historically, the first symbolic methods used BDDs.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] After the success of propositional satisfiability in solving the planning problem in artificial intelligence (see satplan) in 1996, the same approach was generalized to model checking for linear temporal logic (LTL): the planning problem corresponds to model checking for safety properties.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] This method is known as bounded model checking.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] The success of Boolean satisfiability solvers in bounded model checking led to the widespread use of satisfiability solvers in symbolic model checking.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] One example of such a system requirement: *Between the time an elevator is called at a floor and the time it opens its doors at that floor, the elevator can arrive at that floor at most twice*.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Here, $\Box$ should be read as "always", $\Diamond$ as "eventually", ${\mathcal {U}}$ as "until" and the other symbols are standard logical symbols, $\lor$ for "or", $\land$ for "and" and $\lnot$ for "not".
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Model-checking tools face a combinatorial blow up of the state-space, commonly known as the state explosion problem, that must be addressed to solve most real-world problems.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] There are several approaches to combat this problem.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Bounded model-checking algorithms unroll the FSM for a fixed number of steps, k , and check whether a property violation can occur in k or fewer steps.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] This typically involves encoding the restricted model as an instance of SAT.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] The process can be repeated with larger and larger values of k until all possible violations have been ruled out (cf.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Iterative deepening depth-first search).
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Abstraction attempts to prove properties of a system by first simplifying it.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] The simplified system usually does not satisfy exactly the same properties as the original one so that a process of refinement may be necessary.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Generally, one requires the abstraction to be *sound* (the properties proved on the abstraction are true of the original system); however, sometimes the abstraction is not *complete* (not all true properties of the original system are true of the abstraction).
[src:openconfig/model-checking] An example of abstraction is to ignore the values of non-Boolean variables and to only consider Boolean variables and the control flow of the program; such an abstraction, though it may appear coarse, may, in fact, be sufficient to prove e.g. properties of mutual exclusion.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Counterexample-guided abstraction refinement (CEGAR) begins checking with a coarse (i.e. imprecise) abstraction and iteratively refines it.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] When a violation (i.e. counterexample) is found, the tool analyzes it for feasibility (i.e., is the violation genuine or the result of an incomplete abstraction?).
[src:openconfig/model-checking] If the violation is feasible, it is reported to the user.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] If it is not, the proof of infeasibility is used to refine the abstraction and checking begins again.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Model-checking tools were initially developed to reason about the logical correctness of discrete state systems, but have since been extended to deal with real-time and limited forms of hybrid systems.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] Model checking is also studied in the field of computational complexity theory.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] This problem is in the circuit class **AC0**.
[src:openconfig/model-checking] These results have been extended to the task of enumerating all solutions to a first-order formula with free variables.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The **Network Configuration Protocol** (**NETCONF**) is a network management protocol developed and standardized by the IETF.
[src:openconfig/netconf] It was developed in the NETCONF working group and published in December 2006 as RFC 4741 and later revised in June 2011 and published as RFC 6241.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The NETCONF protocol specification is an Internet Standards Track document.
[src:openconfig/netconf] NETCONF provides mechanisms to install, manipulate, and delete the configuration of network devices.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Its operations are realized on top of a simple Remote Procedure Call (RPC) layer.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The NETCONF protocol uses an Extensible Markup Language (XML) based data encoding for the configuration data as well as the protocol messages.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The protocol messages are exchanged on top of a secure transport protocol.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The Operations layer defines a set of base protocol operations to retrieve and edit the configuration data.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The Messages layer provides a mechanism for encoding remote procedure calls (RPCs) and notifications.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The Secure Transport layer provides a secure and reliable transport of messages between a client and a server.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The NETCONF protocol has been implemented in network devices such as routers and switches by some major equipment vendors.
[src:openconfig/netconf] One particular strength of NETCONF is its support for robust configuration change using transactions involving a number of devices.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The IETF developed the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) in the late 1980s and it proved to be a very popular network management protocol.
[src:openconfig/netconf] In the early part of the 21st century it became apparent that in spite of what was originally intended, SNMP was not being used to configure network equipment, but was mainly being used for network monitoring.
[src:openconfig/netconf] In June 2002, the Internet Architecture Board and key members of the IETF's network management community got together with network operators to discuss the situation.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The results of this meeting are documented in RFC 3535.
[src:openconfig/netconf] It turned out that each network operator was primarily using a different proprietary command-line interface (CLI) to configure their devices.
[src:openconfig/netconf] This had a number of features that the operators liked, including the fact that it was text-based, as opposed to the BER-encoded SNMP.
[src:openconfig/netconf] In addition, many equipment vendors did not provide the option to completely configure their devices via SNMP.
[src:openconfig/netconf] As operators generally liked to write scripts to help manage their boxes, they found the SNMP CLI lacking in a number of ways.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Most notably was the unpredictable nature of the output.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The content and formatting of output was prone to change in unpredictable ways.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Around this same time, Juniper Networks had been using an XML-based network management approach.
[src:openconfig/netconf] This was brought to the IETF and shared with the broader community.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Collectively, these two events led the IETF in May 2003 to the creation of the NETCONF working group.
[src:openconfig/netconf] This working group was chartered to work on a network configuration protocol, which would better align with the needs of network operators and equipment vendors.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The first version of the base NETCONF protocol was published as RFC 4741 in December 2006.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Several extensions were published in subsequent years (notifications in RFC 5277 in July 2008, partial locks in RFC 5717 in December 2009, with-defaults in RFC 6243 in June 2011, system notifications in RFC 6470 in February 2012, access control in RFC 6536 in March 2012).
[src:openconfig/netconf] A revised version of the base NETCONF protocol was published as RFC 6241 in June 2011.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The content of NETCONF operations is well-formed XML.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Most content is related to network management.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Subsequently, support for encoding in JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) was also added.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The NETMOD working group has completed work to define a "human-friendly" modeling language for defining the semantics of operational data, configuration data, notifications, and operations, called YANG.
[src:openconfig/netconf] YANG is defined in RFC 6020 (version 1) and RFC 7950 (version 1.1), and is accompanied by the "Common YANG Data Types" found in RFC 6991.
[src:openconfig/netconf] During the summer of 2010, the NETMOD working group was re-chartered to work on core configuration models (system, interface, and routing) as well as work on compatibility with the SNMP modeling language.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Basic NETCONF functionality can be extended by the definition of NETCONF capabilities.
[src:openconfig/netconf] The set of additional protocol features that an implementation supports is communicated between the server and the client during the capability exchange portion of session setup.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Mandatory protocol features are not included in the capability exchange since they are assumed.
[src:openconfig/netconf] RFC 4741 defines a number of optional capabilities including :xpath and :validate.
[src:openconfig/netconf] A capability to support subscribing and receiving asynchronous event notifications is published in RFC 5277.
[src:openconfig/netconf] This document defines the <create-subscription> operation, which enables creating real-time and replay subscriptions.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Notifications are then sent asynchronously using the <notification> construct.
[src:openconfig/netconf] It also defines the :interleave capability, which when supported with the basic :notification capability facilitates the processing of other NETCONF operations while the subscription is active.
[src:openconfig/netconf] A capability to support partial locking of the running configuration is defined in RFC 5717.
[src:openconfig/netconf] This allows multiple sessions to edit non-overlapping sub-trees within the running configuration.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Without this capability, the only lock available is for the entire configuration.
[src:openconfig/netconf] A capability to monitor the NETCONF protocol is defined in RFC 6022.
[src:openconfig/netconf] This document contains a data model including information about NETCONF datastores, sessions, locks, and statistics that facilitates the management of a NETCONF server.
[src:openconfig/netconf] It also defines methods for NETCONF clients to discover data models supported by a NETCONF server and defines the <get-schema> operation to retrieve them.
[src:openconfig/netconf] Every NETCONF message is a well-formed XML document.
[src:openconfig/netconf] An RPC result is linked to an RPC invocation by a message-id attribute.
[src:openconfig/netconf] NETCONF messages can be pipelined, i.e., a client can invoke multiple RPCs without having to wait for RPC result messages first.
[src:openconfig/netconf] RPC messages are defined in RFC 6241 and notification messages are defined in RFC 5277.
[src:openconfig/network-management] A number of applications and protocols exist to support network and network device management.
[src:openconfig/network-management] Network management allows IT professionals to monitor network components within a large network area.
[src:openconfig/network-management] Access methods include the SNMP, command-line interface (CLI), custom XML, CMIP, Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), Transaction Language 1 (TL1), CORBA, NETCONF, RESTCONF and the Java Management Extensions (JMX).
[src:openconfig/network-management] Schemas include the Structure of Management Information (SMI), YANG, WBEM, the Common Information Model (CIM Schema), and MTOSI amongst others.
[src:openconfig/network-management] Effective network management can provide positive strategic impacts.
[src:openconfig/network-management] For example, in the case of developing an infrastructure, providing participants with some interactive space allows them to collaborate with each other, thereby promoting overall benefits.
[src:openconfig/network-management] At the same time, the value of network management to the strategic network is also affected by the relationship between participants.
[src:openconfig/network-management] Active participation, interaction and collaboration can make them more trusting of each other and enhance cohesion.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Google developed Protocol Buffers for internal use and provided a code generator for multiple languages under an open-source license.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] The design goals for Protocol Buffers emphasized simplicity and performance.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] In particular, it was designed to be smaller and faster than XML.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is widely used at Google for storing and interchanging all kinds of structured information.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] The method serves as a basis for a custom remote procedure call (RPC) system that is used for nearly all inter-machine communication at Google.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Protocol Buffers is similar to the Apache Thrift, Amazon Ion, and Microsoft Bond protocols, offering a concrete RPC protocol stack to use for defined services called gRPC.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Data structure schemas (called *messages*) and services are described in a proto definition file (`.proto`) and compiled with `protoc`.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] This compilation generates code that can be invoked by a sender or recipient of these data structures.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] For example, `example.pb.cc` and `example.pb.h` are generated from `example.proto`.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] They define C++ classes for each message and service in `example.proto`.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Canonically, messages are serialized into a binary wire format which is compact, forward- and backward-compatible, but not self-describing (that is, there is no way to tell the names, meaning, or full datatypes of fields without an external specification).
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] There is no defined way to include or refer to such an external specification (schema) within a Protocol Buffers file.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] The officially supported implementation includes an ASCII serialization format, but this format—though self-describing—loses the forward- and backward-compatibility behavior, and is thus not a good choice for applications other than human editing and debugging.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Though the primary purpose of Protocol Buffers is to facilitate network communication, its simplicity and speed make Protocol Buffers an alternative to data-centric C++ classes and structs, especially where interoperability with other languages or systems might be needed in the future.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] The format is best suited for small data chunks that don't exceed a few megabytes and can be loaded/sent into memory right away and therefore is not a streamable format.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] The library doesn't provide compression out of the box.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] The format also isn't well supported in non–object-oriented languages (e.g.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] A schema for a particular use of protocol buffers associates data types with field names, using integers to identify each field.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] The `Point` message defines two mandatory data items, `x` and `y`.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] The tag is defined after the equal sign.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] The `Line` and `Polyline` messages, which both use `Point`, demonstrate how composition works in Protocol Buffers.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] `Polyline` has a `repeated` field, and thus `Polyline` behaves like a set of points (of unspecified number).
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] This schema can subsequently be compiled for use by one or more programming languages.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Google provides a compiler called `protoc` which can produce output for C++, Java or Python.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Other schema compilers are available from other sources to create language-dependent output for over 20 other languages.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 2.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java, C#, and Python.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Protobuf 3.0 provides a code generator for C++, Java (including JavaNano, a dialect intended for low-resource environments), Kotlin, Python, Go, Ruby, Objective-C, C#, PHP, Dart.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] It also supports JavaScript since 3.0.0-beta-2.
[src:openconfig/protocol-buffers] Third-party implementations are also available for Ada, Ballerina, C, C++, Dart, Elixir, Erlang, Haskell, JavaScript, Julia, Nim, Perl, PHP, Prolog, R, Rust, Scala, and Swift.
[src:openconfig/yang] YANG enables comprehensive network automation by providing a standardized way to model the configuration and state data of network elements.
[src:openconfig/yang] The language can be used to define the format of event notifications emitted by network devices and allows data modelers to define the signature of RPCs that can be invoked on network elements via the NETCONF protocol.
[src:openconfig/yang] Being protocol-independent, YANG models can be converted into various encoding formats, including XML, JSON, and CBOR, depending on the network configuration protocol's support.
[src:openconfig/yang] YANG is a modular language and represents data structures in a hierarchical tree format.
[src:openconfig/yang] It includes numerous built-in data types, with the capability for users to derive additional application-specific types.
[src:openconfig/yang] More complex reusable data structures can be represented as "groupings," which promote model reusability and consistency.
[src:openconfig/yang] YANG data models can use XPath expressions to define constraints on the elements of a YANG data model, enabling validation of configuration data before it is committed to devices.
[src:openconfig/yang] YANG has become the de facto standard for modeling network device configurations across the telecommunications industry and is widely supported by major network equipment manufacturers.
[src:openconfig/yang] It plays a crucial role in software-defined networking (SDN) and network function virtualization (NFV) environments by providing a consistent interface for programmatic network management.
[src:openconfig/yang] Many network management protocols have associated data modeling languages.
[src:openconfig/yang] The first widely deployed Internet standard for network management was the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP).
[src:openconfig/yang] The data modeling language associated with SNMP was called the Structure of Management Information (SMI).
[src:openconfig/yang] The SMI language itself was based on the 1988 version of the Abstract Syntax Notation One (ASN.1).
[src:openconfig/yang] The current version of the SMI language, SMIv2 defined in RFC 2578, 2579 and 2580, has developed into an extended subset of ASN.1.
[src:openconfig/yang] In the late 1990s, a project was started to create a replacement for SMIv2, which was called SMIng.
[src:openconfig/yang] One motivation was to decouple SMIng from the management protocol SNMP and to give SMIng a syntactic structure that is both easy to parse for computer programs and easy to learn for people familiar with programming languages that use a C-like notation.
[src:openconfig/yang] While the SMIng project did not succeed in the IETF, the SMIng specifications were published as experimental documents in May 2004 (RFC 3780, 3781).
[src:openconfig/yang] Soon after the development of the NETCONF protocol in the IETF, it became clear that a data modeling language was needed to define data models manipulated by the NETCONF protocol.
[src:openconfig/yang] A design team created a proposal that became the basis of the YANG language.
[src:openconfig/yang] The syntactic structure and the base type system was essentially borrowed from SMIng.
[src:openconfig/yang] However, based on the lessons learned from the SMIng project, no attempts were made to make the YANG protocol neutral.
[src:openconfig/yang] Instead, YANG ties into concepts of the NETCONF protocol, such as the assumption that data model instances can be serialized into XML.
[src:openconfig/yang] Standardization of YANG started with the formation of the NETMOD working group in April 2008.
[src:openconfig/yang] The YANG 1.0 specification was published as RFC 6020 in October 2010.
[src:openconfig/yang] Recently, the NETMOD working group has been working on YANG 1.1, which has been published in August 2016 in RFC 7950.
[src:openconfig/yang] The following YANG module `example-sports` shows a data model for team sports.
[src:openconfig/yang] The module declares a namespace and a prefix and imports the type library module `ietf-yang-types` before defining the type `season`.
[src:openconfig/yang] It then defines a container `sports` that includes a list of `person`s and a list of `team`s.
[src:openconfig/yang] A team has a list of players that reference persons via the `leafref` type and its `path` restriction.
